[[File:AkerbladhLupinoLane.jpg|thumb|right|300px|"[[Lupino Lane]]" comic strip, drawn by Alex Akerbladh, from ''[[Film Fun]]'', 1927]]
'''Alexander''' ('''Alex''') '''Akerbladh''' was a [[Sweden|Swedish]]-born comics artist who drew for the [[Amalgamated Press]] in the UK from the 1900s to the 1950s.  Born in [[Sundsvall]], Sweden<ref name="lambiek">[http://lambiek.net/artists/a/akerbladh_alex.htm Alex Akerbladh on Lambiek Comiclopedia]</ref> on 25 April 1886,<ref name="clark">Alan Clark, ''Dictionary of British Comic Artists, Writers and Editors'', The British Library, 1998, p. 1-2</ref> he studied architecture at [[Glasgow School of Art]], and became an apprentice to Sir [[John James Burnet]] for seven years, before studying art at the [[St John's Wood Art School]] in [[London]] under Leonard Walker, and in [[Munich]] under Anton Binder in 1916. He painted interiors and figures in oils and watercolours.<ref name="lambiek" />

His earliest known comics work was "Hounslow Heath the Highwayman" for ''[[Illustrated Chips]]'' in 1909. In 1916 he drew a celebrity comic based on vaudeville comedian [[Little Tich]]. <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/a/akerbladh_alex.htm</ref>He went on to draw for many titles from then until the late 1930s, including ''[[Comic Cuts]]'', ''[[Firefly (comic)|Firefly]]'', ''[[Jester (comic)|Jester]]'', ''[[Kinema Comic]]'', ''[[Sports Fun]]'', ''[[Butterfly (comic)|Butterfly]]'', ''[[Larks (comic)|Larks]]'', ''[[Merry and Bright]]'', ''[[Jingles (comic)|Jingles]]'' and ''[[Crackers (comic)|Crackers]]'', including painting covers for ''Crackers'' annuals. From the late 1930s to the early 1950s his work appeared primarily in ''[[Radio Fun]]'', where he drew "[[Flanagan and Allen]]", "[[Bob Hope]] and [[Jerry Colonna (entertainer)|Jerry Colonna]]", and "[[Arthur Askey]] and [[Anthea Askey|Anthea]]". His last known work was for ''[[TV Fun]]'' in 1953.<ref name="clark" />

A freelancer, he worked from home, and his pages are said to have arrived at the AP "in grubby condition, with no trouble taken to erase pencil marks or spilled ink".<ref name="clark" /> He lived for a time in [[France]], and is believed to have retired to [[South Africa]], where he died<ref name="clark" /> in 1958.<ref name="lambiek" />

